This question is challenging, but can be solved in an elegant way using
a Taylor series.

To begin with, rewrite the sum as:

\begin{align*}
\sum_{k = 0}^{\infty}\frac{1}{e^{k}k!} &= \sum_{k = 0}^{\infty}\frac{e^{-k}}{k!} = \sum_{k = 0}^{\infty}\frac{(e^{-1})^{k}}{k!}\end{align*} Next, set \emph{x = e\textsuperscript{-1}} to obtain

\begin{align*}\sum_{k = 0}^{\infty}\frac{(e^{-1})^{k}}{k!} = \sum_{k = 0}^{\infty}\frac{x^{k}}{k!}\end{align*}

The last sum, however, is the Taylor series of the exponential function,

\begin{align*}\sum_{k = 0}^{\infty}\frac{x^{k}}{k!} = e^{x}\end{align*}

Plugging \emph{x = e\textsuperscript{-1}} back in we find that our final
answer is

\begin{align*}{\color{blue}\sum_{k = 0}^{\infty}\frac{1}{e^{k}k!} = e^{\left(e^{-1}\right)}}\end{align*}
